                    <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed mb-6">
                        The maritime industry is facing a <strong>"regulatory cliff"</strong> driven by the IMO's CII (Carbon Intensity Indicator) and EEXI (Energy Efficiency Existing Ship Index) regulations.
                    </p>
                    <p class="mb-6">
                        <strong>The Specific 'Why':</strong> 45% of the global tanker and bulker fleet will be non-compliant by 2026 without intervention. Traditional drydocks are booked out 3 years in advance. 
                    </p>
                    <p class="mb-6">
                        <strong>The 'How':</strong> The profitable niche is <strong>Autonomous Hull Cleaning & Inspection Robotics</strong>. Unlike heavy retrofits (scrubbers), robots offer instant 5-15% fuel savings by removing biofouling, improving CII ratings immediately without taking the ship out of service.
                    </p>
                    <div class="bg-indigo-50 border-l-4 border-indigo-600 p-4 rounded-r-md">
                        <p class="font-bold text-indigo-900">VC Insight:</p>
                        <p class="text-indigo-800 text-sm">We are betting on "Service-as-a-Software" (SaaS) models where hardware is deployed, but revenue is recurring per cleaning/inspection.</p>
